WEBVTT

00:08.880 --> 00:12.880
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:28.520 --> 00:33.800
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:33.800 --> 00:38.100
And here are your hosts.

00:42.800 --> 00:44.900
This is Daryl Lane and David Cruz.

00:45.260 --> 00:48.920
Norman Spenrad has strong opinions about science fiction in its place in today's world.

00:49.340 --> 00:53.200
As a noted author who helped bring the science fiction new wave to this country, and as a

00:53.200 --> 00:57.080
two-time president of the Science Fiction Writers of America, Spenrad's ideas should

00:57.080 --> 00:57.540
be heard.

00:57.940 --> 01:01.160
One thing he feels strongly about is that science fiction has not been treated fairly

01:01.160 --> 01:01.900
by book reviewers.

01:02.700 --> 01:11.380
As a category, it is treated very unfairly and very cavalierly by the powers that be,

01:11.460 --> 01:17.700
which is mainly the New York Times book review and the New York Review of Books and the so-called

01:17.700 --> 01:21.680
New York Literary Establishment, which really does have a very heavy effect on the way books

01:21.680 --> 01:22.040
are published.

01:22.820 --> 01:27.560
These people, for instance, came down on the American Book Awards, succeeded in getting

01:27.560 --> 01:29.820
science fiction knocked out of the American Book Awards.

01:51.600 --> 01:55.520
As president of the Science Fiction Writers of America, Spenrad has worked for some changes

01:55.520 --> 01:56.120
in the field.

02:50.520 --> 02:54.980
He thinks general readers should be made more aware of science fiction's unique possibilities

02:54.980 --> 02:56.340
and its genuine value.

02:56.680 --> 03:00.500
We asked him if science fiction movies have a positive or negative influence on the public's

03:00.500 --> 03:01.300
image of the field.

03:02.360 --> 03:15.040
I don't think they detract from it either.

03:15.280 --> 03:17.980
If there are some better, more sophisticated movies, they might help.

03:19.060 --> 03:23.580
As it is, it's just kind of neutral publicity, people more aware that it exists.

03:23.780 --> 03:28.780
I think it's positive and will prove to be positive in the long-range because a lot

03:28.780 --> 03:32.520
of people are being introduced to the imagery of science fiction, with which they are unfamiliar

03:32.520 --> 03:33.640
through these movies.

03:34.720 --> 03:38.780
If you look at the evolution in the movies, you find that in the earlier science fiction

03:38.780 --> 03:42.820
movies, if you're going into space or whatever, you had to spend like half an hour setting

03:42.820 --> 03:43.240
a thing.

03:43.600 --> 03:45.640
This is a spaceship that takes off from the Earth.

03:45.820 --> 03:46.840
People float around it.

03:47.040 --> 03:50.820
You have to familiarize the audience with all this unfamiliar imagery.

03:51.060 --> 03:54.720
Now they can just start a movie bang right off, in a galaxy far away.

03:55.060 --> 03:55.240
Boom.

03:55.980 --> 03:57.820
Here's a spaceship in the stromo pow.

03:57.820 --> 04:01.400
In other words, the first half hour of the conventional old-time science fiction movie

04:01.400 --> 04:04.100
is gone because people are now familiar with this imagery.

04:04.920 --> 04:09.960
I think these movies have brought a lot of new people into familiarity with these images.

04:10.400 --> 04:12.560
They made these images part of the popular culture.

04:13.740 --> 04:18.240
These movies were mainly aimed at kids and adolescents.

04:19.200 --> 04:24.480
Years from now, assuming that these people ever read anything, they'll be ready to read

04:24.480 --> 04:30.080
science fiction of a more serious kind, assuming they're ready to read literature of a more

04:30.080 --> 04:34.540
serious kind at all, because they'll be familiar with the material, familiar with the literature.

04:34.700 --> 04:37.820
It won't seem strange and weird to them because they will have grown up with it.

04:38.300 --> 04:43.760
That's why I think magazines, even magazines like Star-Log say, in that sense will have

04:43.760 --> 04:45.320
a long-term positive impact.

