06:25.200 --> 06:29.640
Norman Spinrad's best-known novel may be Bug Jack Barron, a book which has stirred controversy

06:29.640 --> 06:31.040
in both England and America.

06:31.460 --> 06:35.340
It was published in this country in 1969, and it's a different sort of science fiction

06:35.340 --> 06:35.660
novel.

06:36.020 --> 06:38.100
It's a good example of new wave science fiction.

06:38.520 --> 06:42.800
Character and style are important, and it deals with social issues such as racism, the

06:42.800 --> 06:46.140
establishment, drugs, the power of the media, and radical protests.

06:46.140 --> 06:50.260
There is also a good deal of sex and violence in the book, and the language is highly colored.

06:50.620 --> 06:54.400
But Spinrad, thanks to the plot of the book, conforms to traditional science fiction formulas.

06:55.860 --> 06:59.740
Actually, what I was trying to do in a way, the book has a very traditional plot.

07:00.280 --> 07:04.180
As far as I was concerned, it has a positive hero, it has a negative villain.

07:04.540 --> 07:06.060
The hero wins, the villain loses.

07:06.260 --> 07:11.160
All that stuff that is considered the traditional way of plotting a book.

07:11.780 --> 07:13.860
And yet it's written in a different kind of way.

07:13.860 --> 07:19.340
It kind of takes that superficial kind of plot and treats it in a realistic manner.

07:20.840 --> 07:24.620
The protagonist, Jack Barron, is a powerfully influential television star who has a talk

07:24.620 --> 07:26.260
show watched by 100 million people.

07:26.900 --> 07:30.100
He uses the show as a battlefield to oppose corrupt elements of society.

07:30.480 --> 07:32.580
Spinrad comments on Barron's use of power.

07:33.700 --> 07:37.300
The book is about power.

07:37.720 --> 07:41.140
It's about power itself as neutral as far as I'm concerned.

07:41.360 --> 07:42.600
That's what people do with it that counts.

07:43.440 --> 07:48.860
Barron is a guy who likes power and keeps referring to it as a drug.

07:49.840 --> 07:51.940
And knows that he can become addicted to it.

07:52.600 --> 07:55.260
And for that reason, has decided to stay away from it.

07:55.940 --> 08:00.860
Then he gets drawn back into playing with power because he comes to the conclusion that

08:00.860 --> 08:05.760
it's better for somebody who feels that way about power to be wielding it, than people

08:05.760 --> 08:09.360
who don't have any self-consciousness about the dangers of wielding power.

08:09.960 --> 08:15.780
So in that sense, it's a comment on the power of the media, but it's also a comment on the

08:16.240 --> 08:23.160
morality of power, on the paradox of power, which is that if you leave power to be wielded

08:23.720 --> 08:29.100
by people who do not see the dangers, the personal dangers, the psychological dangers

08:29.100 --> 08:33.320
of being involved with it, then you end up with people like Benedict Howard, Ronald Reagan,

08:33.320 --> 08:40.820
and Richard Nixon who do not have self-consciousness about the personal dangers, the moral dangers

08:40.820 --> 08:42.820
of chasing after power.

08:42.940 --> 08:47.820
Whereas somebody like Barron, who is certainly an imperfect person, as all people are, at

08:47.820 --> 08:53.840
least his saving grace, if he has one, is that he is well aware of the personal dangers

08:53.840 --> 08:57.840
of being involved in a quest for power.

08:58.820 --> 09:02.340
When Spinrad tried to get the novel published in this country, he was unsuccessful.

09:02.340 --> 09:03.380
So he tried and written.

09:03.900 --> 09:07.580
But there was an outcry in Parliament against the book. He relates the story for us.

09:08.100 --> 09:11.500
That novel had a lot of trouble. It was written under contract at double day.

09:11.620 --> 09:16.560
They then rejected it. You have to remember the political climate of the era.

09:16.940 --> 09:20.900
They didn't reject it. They said, we'll publish it if you cut out all the sex, all the swear words,

09:20.980 --> 09:24.500
and all the politics, which was the whole book.

09:25.740 --> 09:30.580
So it took a long time to resell that book here. In the meantime, I took it to Wilfred,

09:30.580 --> 09:33.220
to a Wilfred conference, and Mike Murcock was there.

09:33.320 --> 09:35.540
He read it, he locked it, and he serialized it in New World.

09:35.620 --> 09:39.020
So the first publication was actually in England, in the magazine.

09:40.920 --> 09:45.520
Now, halfway through the serialization, I forget exactly which part, Part 3, Part 4,

09:46.080 --> 09:50.520
W. H. Smith, which was the biggest distributor, still is the biggest distributor in England,

09:51.100 --> 09:53.800
refused to distribute the magazine because of the book in it.

09:54.500 --> 09:56.940
Now at that time, New World had an arts council grant.

09:56.940 --> 09:59.520
The arts council was in the organ of the British government.

10:00.640 --> 10:04.220
Now the arts council supported the magazine against Smith publicly.

10:05.260 --> 10:09.480
And so the flap in Parliament arose when certain right wing members of Parliament

10:09.480 --> 10:15.360
were aghast that an organ of the British government, the arts council, was defending this kind of stuff.

10:16.000 --> 10:18.620
And that's how it became a parliamentary issue.

10:19.940 --> 10:23.800
Bugjack Baron is being made into a movie, with a screenplay by Harlan Ellison

10:23.800 --> 10:27.320
and direction by radical filmmaker Costa Gavras. It should be interesting.

10:27.820 --> 10:29.660
More with Norman Spinrad next time.

