12:06.860 --> 12:11.500
Norman Spinrad's 1979 science fiction novel, A World Between, signaled a change in his fiction.

12:11.800 --> 12:16.800
Spinrad's early work usually contained either subtle or overt criticism of various aspects of society.

12:16.800 --> 12:21.600
Bugjack Baron, the men in the jungle and agent of chaos are good examples of this type.

12:21.980 --> 12:25.800
A World Between is also a socially-oriented novel, but there's a different element in it.

12:26.140 --> 12:26.760
Spinrad explains.

12:27.960 --> 12:38.940
I would say in general that up until, I guess, A World Between really, a lot of my stuff was kind of critical.

12:39.200 --> 12:45.040
Critical of this, of existing societies, critical of various things that were going on.

12:45.040 --> 12:50.440
A World Between is meant as a utopian novel, really, in a kind of way.

12:50.660 --> 12:52.480
And it's a prescriptive kind of book.

12:53.200 --> 12:57.740
It's more of a, instead of presenting critical images of other things,

12:58.000 --> 13:02.840
the idea is to create a more positive image of a more positive kind of future.

13:03.020 --> 13:05.460
I think if you spend enough time criticizing what exists,

13:07.820 --> 13:14.800
at some point you have some kind of moral obligation to present something more positive and replaceably.

13:14.800 --> 13:17.220
To replace what you find negative.

13:21.880 --> 13:24.500
The setting for the novel is a fit one for a utopia.

13:25.000 --> 13:30.640
It takes place on the planet Pacifica, a beautiful world of blue ocean and lush green islands that's been colonized by humans.

13:31.360 --> 13:34.280
Inhabitants of Pacifica live private lives in their isolated islands.

13:34.820 --> 13:38.180
There are no large urban centers to cause pollution, overpopulation or poverty.

13:38.680 --> 13:43.380
Even though they are physically isolated, the Pacificans remain in close electronic contact with one another.

13:43.380 --> 13:49.320
They govern themselves, in fact, with a tight media web that allows them to vote immediately on any issue of importance.

13:49.620 --> 13:53.220
But into this idyllic world comes two opposed political forces from Earth,

13:53.320 --> 13:55.660
bent on the ideological conquest of Pacifica.

13:55.980 --> 13:58.440
One force is the Institute for Transcendental Science,

13:58.840 --> 14:02.580
a powerful organization whose goal is galactic unity under their control.

14:03.060 --> 14:06.180
They are extreme, and Spinrad says they have two basic flaws.

14:07.460 --> 14:12.300
One is the unexamined subtle male, male chauvinist bias of their culture.

14:12.300 --> 14:23.120
And the other one is the ultimate conviction that what they are doing is the absolute most important thing in the universe.

14:23.420 --> 14:31.500
And therefore they are morally entitled to run over other people's cultures and desires.

14:33.060 --> 14:40.980
Absolutism, I guess, would be the kind of theocratic absolutism would be their flaw.

14:40.980 --> 14:45.460
The other force is the Femocrats, a militant women's liberation group that is also an extreme.

14:46.040 --> 14:50.640
The struggle of these two groups for control of planets all across the galaxy is called the Pink and Blue War.

14:50.940 --> 14:57.060
It's clearly a male-female conflict, and so far every planet the two sides have approached has ended up on one side or the other.

14:57.540 --> 15:01.260
But Pacifica is different. Spinrad's utopia is a stable and intelligent one.

15:01.800 --> 15:06.040
The Pacificans reject both extremes and even change the minds of a few of the combatants.

15:06.040 --> 15:11.400
We asked Spinrad about reactions to the book. How did women, for instance, respond to the Femocratic women's livers?

15:12.640 --> 15:27.340
The strange thing about the reaction to that book has been that a certain number of men have reacted in a kind of male liberal guilt, male feminist kind of reaction against that.

15:27.900 --> 15:32.760
But at most part women have liked the book. Women have identified with it more than men.

15:34.280 --> 15:37.700
And actually I even got one or two good reviews in feminist places.

15:38.660 --> 15:42.100
I think that's not quite what I expected, but that seems to be the way it happened.

15:42.280 --> 15:46.680
I have not gotten heavy feminist flanks from that a little bit, but not much.

15:46.860 --> 15:59.400
Not much because I think women who are involved in feminism or have been, or know women who are, can recognize a certain aspect of the feminist movement in the Femocrats.

15:59.400 --> 16:03.960
Whereas men who are trying to show how liberator they are would not dream of admitting such a thing.

16:04.560 --> 16:09.200
A world between. A different sort of book for Norman Spinrad, and we'll have more on him tomorrow.

