17:45.360 --> 17:50.320
Norman Spinrad's most recent novel, Songs from the Stars, was published by Simon and Schuster in 1980.

17:50.820 --> 17:54.680
The book describes a fragmented future society in a world devastated by nuclear war.

17:55.100 --> 17:56.900
This, of course, is a typical Spinrad theme.

17:56.900 --> 18:04.560
But the novel also communicates the sense of wonder characteristic of good science fiction when it describes the marvels of contact with an alien civilization.

18:05.160 --> 18:07.780
Society has split in two factions in Songs from the Stars.

18:08.260 --> 18:16.100
One faction is an Aquarian society which bans all technology, in fact anything having to do with science, since this was what was responsible for almost destroying the Earth.

18:16.480 --> 18:23.460
And the other faction are the black scientists who keep technology alive and maintain an illicit smuggling operation with the Aquarian Society.

18:23.460 --> 18:25.760
Spinrad talks about these opposed factions.

19:01.320 --> 19:05.600
It's a book about horror unity, I guess.

19:07.060 --> 19:10.480
As usual, with Spinrad, the book's conflict reflects current social conditions.

19:11.280 --> 19:13.860
And then, you know, a mirror is the present thing in our society.

19:14.140 --> 19:20.500
Where on the one hand you have a great big space movement, people wanting to get into space, and all the old people and all that stuff.

19:20.580 --> 19:29.900
On the other hand you have a real atavistic, neo-Luddite movement, an anti-nuclear movement which is really kind of willfully ignorant of a lot of things.

19:31.740 --> 19:35.820
In a way, these are the two things that could bring about the crash.

19:38.940 --> 19:41.080
And as well as what with some armaments.

19:41.280 --> 19:46.840
So I think it's basically a book about the grand philosophical attempt at apoc.

19:46.880 --> 19:53.680
Is to try and bridge the gap between science and reason and feeling emotion and mysticism.

19:54.680 --> 19:59.900
And to point to a horror unity between the two things.

19:59.900 --> 20:06.160
And away from the false dichotomies and false dualisms, which seem to be really destroying Western civilization.

20:06.380 --> 20:11.860
The protagonist in the book is a laid back Aquarian, clear blue loo.

20:12.340 --> 20:15.780
Along with his girl and a scientist, he travels up to a satellite circling the Earth.

20:16.260 --> 20:21.880
There are the three of them receive communication from some incredibly advanced alien civilizations in another part of the galaxy.

20:22.440 --> 20:29.480
With the knowledge sent by the helpful aliens, it seems the humans will solve their own problems, unite, and start progressing toward the stars once more.

20:29.480 --> 20:35.540
We asked Spinrad that if and when we contact an alien civilization, is it likely they will be helpful rather than hostile?

20:37.340 --> 20:43.260
As I said in the book, I do believe that any civilization that's going to last a million years,

20:43.380 --> 20:47.120
it's going to be a million years or whatever, or even a hundred thousand years more advanced than us,

20:47.420 --> 20:50.720
they've been around that much longer, had that much more advanced science.

20:51.600 --> 20:58.200
If it's going to survive to that length of its own history, it's got to solve it, you know, it's got to be by that time.

20:59.320 --> 21:03.300
Philosophically and emotionally pretty together, or who long since it destroyed itself.

21:03.560 --> 21:10.040
I mean, we certainly will not survive a million years of our own history if it continues as it has, you know.

21:10.660 --> 21:14.580
In order that any civilization that survives a million years of its own history,

21:14.660 --> 21:20.040
has had to have gotten its political, psychological, and philosophical act together.

21:21.020 --> 21:22.680
And I don't see why, you know.

21:25.440 --> 21:31.220
And I do believe that if and when we run into that kind of really advanced civilization,

21:31.640 --> 21:36.460
that they will, if not be directly, actively helpful,

21:36.600 --> 21:43.040
certainly will be benign and will not be interested in either eating us, or conquering our planet, or blowing us up, or anything like that.

21:44.100 --> 21:49.260
Songs from the Stars is a thoughtfully written book with a theme, but it's also good exciting science fiction.

